<description>Robert joined Arsenal soon after Franceï¿½s triumph at Euro 2000. A quick, skilful ball-player, being equally comfortable on either left or right flank makes him a constant threat. 
Having been a member of Le Bleus' World Cup winning squad in 1998, Robert joined Arsenal after triumphing at Euro 2000 with France when he set up David Trezeguet's 'golden goal' in the final against Italy. Before long he began to show the sort of form that earned him a regular spot in his national side. A quick, skilful ball-player, equally comfortable on either left or right flank and exciting to watch when attacking opposition defences, Robert played a key role in the Gunners' 2002 Premiership success as well as winning the FA Cup in 2002 and 2003. He also won the Football Writers' Player of the Year award in 2002. 
 'Bobby' continued to perform well for his country and was a member of the team that defeated Japan to win the FIFA Confederations Cup during the summer of 2001, and winning the Player of the Tournament award. Now with over 60 caps to his name, Robert made his full international debut against Mexico in August 1996. 
 Born in Reims, Robert began at his local club before moving on to Metz (French League Cup winner in 1996) then Olympique Marseille (UEFA Cup finalist in 1999).</description>

